abstract.para:
This package contains Large Woody Debris (LWD) Zone data for data collection years 2006-2017 for the Long Term Aquatic Monitoring (LTAM) program in Seattle Public Utilities Cedar River Watershed Habitat Conservation Plan in North Bend, Washington. Four zones were classified in and adjacent to the stream channel, and woody debris length was measured in each of the four zones. Small end and large end diameter was also measured.
For more detailed information on the LTAM program and methods, refer to the LTAM Methods and Reports data package.

description.para: The minimum large woody debris (LWD) size to be counted in the survey was minimum 4 inch sustained diameter for a minimum of 6 feet in length. Four zones were classified in and adjacent to the stream channel, and woody debris length was measured in each of the four zones. Small end and large end diameter was also measured for individual pieces. If there were (5) qualifying pieces that touched, these pieces were grouped into a LWD jam, where a percentage of volume in each of the for zones was estimated and qualifying pieces were tallied.

abstract.para: Long Term Aquatic Monitoring (LTAM) pebble count summary data and individual working data, 2006-2017, in support of the Cedar River Watershed Habitat Conservation Plan, for Seattle Public Utilities in North Bend, Washington. Field methods were based on Wolman Pebble Count methods, e.g. using the blind touch method off the tip of the boot and measuring intermediate b-axis for at least 100 particles, bankfull to bankfull, for all channels at a particular cross section. Data is summarized for each cross section for each year at each site, as well as all cross sections for each year at each site, into particle size class distribution classes and noting p-value significance.
